$ SQLite functions
@ functions

  → development/databases/SQLite/functions/hex[`hex(val)`] returns a hexadecimal representation of the internally stored bytes for `val`.

  → development/databases/SQLite/functions/random[`random()`] returns a pseudo-random number in the range between -9223372036854775808 and +9223372036854775807.

  → development/databases/SQLite/functions/randomblob[`randomblob()`]

  → development/databases/SQLite/functions/regexp[`val regexp(pat)`]: search for records with → development/regular-expressions[regular expressions].

  → development/databases/SQLite/functions/substr[`substr(str, beg, len)`]

  → development/databases/SQLite/functions/quote[`quote(val)`] returns a string that, as expression, evaluates to the same value as was quoted.

  → development/databases/SQLite/functions/sqlite_version[`sqlite_version()`] returns a the version of the running *SQLite library*.

  → development/databases/SQLite/functions/typeof[`typeof(val)`] returns a string that indicates the → development/databases/SQLite/datatypes[datatype] of `val`.

  → development/databases/SQLite/functions/upper-lower[`upper(str)` and `lower(str)`] convert → development/Unicode/ASCII[ASCII] characters to upper or lower.

  → development/databases/SQLite/functions/zeroblob[`zeroblob(n)`] returns a → development/databases/SQLite/datatypes/blob[blob] with `n` bytes, each being `0`.

  → development/databases/SQLite/functions/date-time-related[Date and time related functiones]

{ changes #changes

  gh|about-sqlite|/functions/changes.sql||

  Compare with → #total_changes

  In SQLite's → development/databases/SQLite/shell[shell], this function is automatically called if `.changes on` is set.

